WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.920 --> 00:00:04.330
SPEAKER 1: I'm excited to
introduce David Kaplan, who

00:00:04.330 --> 00:00:07.547
is the co-author for this
book that Joel Peterson

00:00:07.547 --> 00:00:09.130
wrote in conjunction
with David, which

00:00:09.130 --> 00:00:10.213
is "The 10 Laws of Trust."

00:00:10.213 --> 00:00:12.030
We're going to be
talking more about it.

00:00:12.030 --> 00:00:14.758
So David, please introduce Joel.

00:00:17.690 --> 00:00:20.180
DAVID KAPLAN: Thank you.

00:00:20.180 --> 00:00:24.280
Showing how old I
am, I remember when

00:00:24.280 --> 00:00:27.450
I showed up a little while ago.

00:00:27.450 --> 00:00:31.590
I had my first full-time
journalism job in this building

00:00:31.590 --> 00:00:34.310
back in the age of dinosaurs.

00:00:34.310 --> 00:00:36.030
It was a print newspaper.

00:00:36.030 --> 00:00:38.440
A lot has changed
since then, including

00:00:38.440 --> 00:00:40.280
you guys now being
in the building

00:00:40.280 --> 00:00:44.190
and that newspaper not being
in the building anymore.

00:00:44.190 --> 00:00:47.040
It's a pleasure to be here.

00:00:47.040 --> 00:00:50.120
I met Joel a few
years ago, and have

00:00:50.120 --> 00:00:53.940
come to learn in working with
him why he's considered such

00:00:53.940 --> 00:00:58.130
a treasure among CEOs,
boards-- he's Chairman

00:00:58.130 --> 00:01:02.310
of the Board of JetBlue--
and as a beloved professor

00:01:02.310 --> 00:01:05.710
at Stanford, where he's
mentored many entrepreneurs

00:01:05.710 --> 00:01:09.610
and students who've gone
on to work at Google,

00:01:09.610 --> 00:01:12.090
or who had worked at
Google previously.

00:01:12.090 --> 00:01:16.760
For purposes of this book, I
may be his number-one student.

00:01:16.760 --> 00:01:19.290
When he told me about
the topic and showed

00:01:19.290 --> 00:01:23.970
me some posts he had written
and speeches he had given,

00:01:23.970 --> 00:01:25.340
I was skeptical.

00:01:25.340 --> 00:01:28.050
Was this stuff about trust pap?

00:01:28.050 --> 00:01:29.710
Was he a Pollyanna?

00:01:29.710 --> 00:01:36.220
And as I came to learn from him
over many classes and sessions

00:01:36.220 --> 00:01:40.010
we would have in person and
on the phone electronically,

00:01:40.010 --> 00:01:44.370
and as I helped him form
his thoughts on paper,

00:01:44.370 --> 00:01:47.761
which became this book, I
learned that it isn't, and he's

00:01:47.761 --> 00:01:48.260
not.

00:01:48.260 --> 00:01:50.780
And that's what he's
here to talk about.

00:01:50.780 --> 00:01:53.080
Joel?

00:01:53.080 --> 00:01:57.200
[APPLAUSE]

00:01:58.140 --> 00:02:00.431
JOEL PETERSON: So I think
you're going to interview me.

00:02:00.431 --> 00:02:02.740
But before you do, I just
have to tell a Google story.

00:02:02.740 --> 00:02:05.230
So I teach at Stanford
Business School,

00:02:05.230 --> 00:02:08.009
and the dean there
had Eric Schmidt--

00:02:08.009 --> 00:02:11.130
told Eric Schmidt that he
should sit in on my class.

00:02:11.130 --> 00:02:13.860
Because as he said it,
the room temperature

00:02:13.860 --> 00:02:15.680
is really good in this class.

00:02:15.680 --> 00:02:18.490
And whenever I
teach, I spot people

00:02:18.490 --> 00:02:21.220
who are not part of
the normal classroom,

00:02:21.220 --> 00:02:22.920
and I have them
introduce themselves.

00:02:22.920 --> 00:02:25.820
And this was maybe 10
years ago, or whatever.

00:02:25.820 --> 00:02:28.400
So I called on this
older gentleman

00:02:28.400 --> 00:02:29.650
that was sitting in the class.

00:02:29.650 --> 00:02:31.483
I said, would you please
introduce yourself?

00:02:31.483 --> 00:02:32.990
And he said, hi,
I'm Eric Schmidt.

00:02:32.990 --> 00:02:33.790
Really glad to be here.

00:02:33.790 --> 00:02:35.456
And I said, well,
Eric, you need to tell

00:02:35.456 --> 00:02:36.970
the class who you work for.

00:02:36.970 --> 00:02:40.350
And the class just broke
out into laughter, thinking,

00:02:40.350 --> 00:02:43.090
who is this professor who has
no idea who Eric Schmidt is?

00:02:43.090 --> 00:02:45.450
Now that was before Eric
Schmidt was Eric Schmidt.

00:02:45.450 --> 00:02:48.350
But still, he was a
pretty important guy.

00:02:48.350 --> 00:02:52.850
So I do teach, as David
said, a lot of people who've

00:02:52.850 --> 00:02:55.920
worked at Google, and then a
lot who come out of the GSP

00:02:55.920 --> 00:02:56.760
and come to Google.

00:02:56.760 --> 00:02:58.218
So I'm really
delighted to be here,

00:02:58.218 --> 00:03:01.040
and I think you're doing
it as kind of a Q&amp;A.

00:03:01.040 --> 00:03:03.440
And I don't know where
she's headed either.

00:03:03.440 --> 00:03:04.481
SPEAKER 1: You know what?

00:03:04.481 --> 00:03:07.187
When I'm given a mic and a free
forum to ask any questions,

00:03:07.187 --> 00:03:07.686
I'm excited.

00:03:07.686 --> 00:03:08.500
JOEL PETERSON: You're
supposed to be here.

00:03:08.500 --> 00:03:09.333
SPEAKER 1: Yeah, OK.

00:03:09.333 --> 00:03:10.429
We'll switch over.

00:03:10.429 --> 00:03:11.720
Already playing musical chairs.

00:03:11.720 --> 00:03:15.720
But welcome officially, Joel,
to Talks at Google and so

00:03:15.720 --> 00:03:17.330
have you here in New York City.

00:03:17.330 --> 00:03:21.204
So before we get right
into the book about trust,

00:03:21.204 --> 00:03:23.120
I'm sure you're all
interested in hearing more

00:03:23.120 --> 00:03:25.130
about your professional
development and all

00:03:25.130 --> 00:03:27.632
the successes you've
had in your career.

00:03:27.632 --> 00:03:29.840
So can you tell us a little
bit about your background

00:03:29.840 --> 00:03:33.270
and how you got
into the hotseat?

00:03:33.270 --> 00:03:35.436
JOEL PETERSON: So I went
to Harvard Business School,

00:03:35.436 --> 00:03:38.700
and there was a guy who put a
3" by 5" card on the bulletin

00:03:38.700 --> 00:03:41.340
board that said, looking
for a French speaker

00:03:41.340 --> 00:03:43.650
to go to the French
Riviera and work.

00:03:43.650 --> 00:03:45.550
And I just thought,
my high school buddies

00:03:45.550 --> 00:03:47.830
are never going to believe this.

00:03:47.830 --> 00:03:51.490
And so I got interested,
ended up taking the job.

00:03:51.490 --> 00:03:54.000
I went not to the
French Riviera,

00:03:54.000 --> 00:03:56.200
but to Paris, and then to Lyon.

00:03:56.200 --> 00:03:57.840
Ended up in the real
estate business.

00:03:57.840 --> 00:04:00.095
Long story short, there
was a lot of workouts,

00:04:00.095 --> 00:04:02.280
a lot of issues at that time.

00:04:02.280 --> 00:04:05.520
I became the treasurer
of the company at I

00:04:05.520 --> 00:04:08.270
think about age 29, or
something like that.

00:04:08.270 --> 00:04:09.684
And we didn't have any cash.

00:04:09.684 --> 00:04:11.850
If you know what a treasurer
does, they manage cash.

00:04:11.850 --> 00:04:12.950
We didn't have any.

00:04:12.950 --> 00:04:13.890
[LAUGHTER]

00:04:13.890 --> 00:04:18.089
And that caused the chief
financial officer to leave,

00:04:18.089 --> 00:04:19.930
and I became the chief
financial officer.

00:04:19.930 --> 00:04:22.264
So at age 29, I was the
chief financial officer

00:04:22.264 --> 00:04:24.180
of the largest private
real estate development

00:04:24.180 --> 00:04:25.500
company in the world.

00:04:25.500 --> 00:04:28.304
And I didn't have any
idea what I was doing.

00:04:28.304 --> 00:04:30.220
And one thing led to
another, and I ultimately

00:04:30.220 --> 00:04:35.120
ended up as the CEO of
Trammell Crow Company.

00:04:35.120 --> 00:04:39.300
And then I ended up teaching,
starting to teach at Stanford.

00:04:39.300 --> 00:04:43.360
And then I started my
own investment firm,

00:04:43.360 --> 00:04:45.100
private equity,
growth capital firm.

00:04:45.100 --> 00:04:48.150
And then I started a
ventures firm, and then

00:04:48.150 --> 00:04:51.645
a couple of real estate
funds, and other things.

00:04:51.645 --> 00:04:54.844
So we back maybe now
200 entrepreneurs.

00:04:54.844 --> 00:04:56.260
So I started a
number of companies

00:04:56.260 --> 00:04:57.676
and backed a lot
of entrepreneurs.

00:04:57.676 --> 00:05:02.190
And it's really from that that
these observations about trust

00:05:02.190 --> 00:05:02.690
come.

00:05:02.690 --> 00:05:06.290
Because I've seen companies
that have failed or not based on

00:05:06.290 --> 00:05:08.884
whether or not they build
a high-trust culture.

00:05:08.884 --> 00:05:10.800
SPEAKER 1: And so I guess
that's a great segue

00:05:10.800 --> 00:05:11.832
into the next question.

00:05:11.832 --> 00:05:13.540
So in the book, in a
lot of your writing,

00:05:13.540 --> 00:05:16.640
you talk about how your
life is a testament

00:05:16.640 --> 00:05:18.240
to the power of trust.

00:05:18.240 --> 00:05:20.980
And so in your professional--
in your career,

00:05:20.980 --> 00:05:22.600
in your personal
life, how have you

00:05:22.600 --> 00:05:25.440
instilled trust in
your relationships?

00:05:25.440 --> 00:05:28.940
JOEL PETERSON: So I
started out with parents

00:05:28.940 --> 00:05:30.150
who really were trusting.

00:05:30.150 --> 00:05:31.160
It was a gift.

00:05:31.160 --> 00:05:32.920
I didn't really realize.

00:05:32.920 --> 00:05:35.030
But if I would make
a mistake, they

00:05:35.030 --> 00:05:37.950
would see that as a preamble
to success the next time.

00:05:37.950 --> 00:05:40.410
Have any of you read
Carol Dweck's book?

00:05:40.410 --> 00:05:42.180
It's phenomenal, I think.

00:05:42.180 --> 00:05:45.180
It's really changed--
I only see a few people

00:05:45.180 --> 00:05:46.180
nodding their heads.

00:05:46.180 --> 00:05:49.760
But you really ought to read
this book called "Mindset."

00:05:49.760 --> 00:05:54.270
And it's fundamentally about
accepting failure, seeing

00:05:54.270 --> 00:05:55.850
failure as a
preamble to success.

00:05:55.850 --> 00:06:00.460
Well, I started out with
parents that saw that in me.

00:06:00.460 --> 00:06:04.190
And then what I try to do is
mimic that in relationships.

00:06:04.190 --> 00:06:06.180
And most of the time, it works.

00:06:06.180 --> 00:06:08.040
So most of the
time, trust works.

00:06:08.040 --> 00:06:10.170
If you extend trust
to people, they

00:06:10.170 --> 00:06:12.066
don't like to disappoint you.

00:06:12.066 --> 00:06:14.900
They fulfill what they promise.

00:06:14.900 --> 00:06:16.530
You have more trust in them.

00:06:16.530 --> 00:06:18.270
You trust them with
something greater,

00:06:18.270 --> 00:06:20.490
and it becomes this
virtuous cycle.

00:06:20.490 --> 00:06:22.040
And so it's really
been repeated.

00:06:22.040 --> 00:06:25.670
So I have seven children,
and I always say to people,

00:06:25.670 --> 00:06:27.526
I like most of my
kids most of the time.

00:06:27.526 --> 00:06:28.026
[LAUGHTER]

00:06:28.026 --> 00:06:31.410
And so most of them
don't disappoint me.

00:06:31.410 --> 00:06:34.300
Most of them really live up
to-- and if I trust them,

00:06:34.300 --> 00:06:36.240
they will actually
try to live up to it.

00:06:36.240 --> 00:06:37.380
And so I think that's
actually-- there's

00:06:37.380 --> 00:06:40.040
a principle in there for people
who are building businesses,

00:06:40.040 --> 00:06:41.550
who are growing businesses.

00:06:41.550 --> 00:06:44.090
Pushing the power to people.

00:06:44.090 --> 00:06:45.970
SPEAKER 1: And so when
you talk about trust

00:06:45.970 --> 00:06:48.770
and personal in your own
house with your family

00:06:48.770 --> 00:06:51.580
and then professionally,
how do you define trust?

00:06:51.580 --> 00:06:53.220
What does that mean to you?

00:06:53.220 --> 00:06:56.790
JOEL PETERSON: So trust is
ceding authority, the ability

00:06:56.790 --> 00:06:59.240
to act to another party.

00:06:59.240 --> 00:07:03.090
So when you give up
control, you have to trust.

00:07:03.090 --> 00:07:05.940
And you're trusting somebody
to look out for you,

00:07:05.940 --> 00:07:07.490
to do what's in your interest.

00:07:07.490 --> 00:07:09.030
We do it all the time.

00:07:09.030 --> 00:07:12.050
We do it with doctors,
dentists, lawyers, accountants.

00:07:12.050 --> 00:07:14.290
We do it professionally
all the time.

00:07:14.290 --> 00:07:17.270
Sometimes in interpersonal
relationships,

00:07:17.270 --> 00:07:20.190
we're a little wary, we're
a little bit cautious.

00:07:20.190 --> 00:07:21.435
And rightfully so.

00:07:21.435 --> 00:07:22.310
We should be careful.

00:07:22.310 --> 00:07:26.100
We should be smart about how
we use this very powerful tool.

00:07:26.100 --> 00:07:29.250
I think trust, the
contract that you and I had

00:07:29.250 --> 00:07:31.960
if we trust each other,
it's kind of a thermonuclear

00:07:31.960 --> 00:07:32.920
contract.

00:07:32.920 --> 00:07:35.626
If done well, it's
really powerful.

00:07:35.626 --> 00:07:37.500
Take us both to places
we'd not otherwise go.

00:07:37.500 --> 00:07:40.159
If poorly done, it
ends in betrayal.

00:07:40.159 --> 00:07:42.700
SPEAKER 1: And so that was going
to be my follow-up question.

00:07:42.700 --> 00:07:45.020
It's like we rehearsed
this already.

00:07:45.020 --> 00:07:48.280
So when you trust somebody
and then they betray you,

00:07:48.280 --> 00:07:50.330
how do you overcome that?

00:07:50.330 --> 00:07:54.220
And how do you re-empower
yourself to trust them again,

00:07:54.220 --> 00:07:56.560
or how do you kind of cope
with that type of situation?

00:07:56.560 --> 00:07:58.810
JOEL PETERSON: So it depends
on the level of betrayal.

00:07:58.810 --> 00:08:01.143
You know, if somebody says
they're going to do something

00:08:01.143 --> 00:08:04.630
and they don't do it, that
is, in a sense, a betrayal.

00:08:04.630 --> 00:08:05.880
But that happens all the time.

00:08:05.880 --> 00:08:09.256
And sometimes, it's for good
reasons that they don't do it.

00:08:09.256 --> 00:08:11.539
And so if it's a
minor betrayal, I

00:08:11.539 --> 00:08:13.580
try to get to the bottom
of it and understand it.

00:08:13.580 --> 00:08:17.360
Because you want to stop those
sorts of things early on.

00:08:17.360 --> 00:08:18.840
Otherwise, they metastasize.

00:08:18.840 --> 00:08:20.731
And you end up not
trusting somebody,

00:08:20.731 --> 00:08:22.230
and it builds, and
you start looking

00:08:22.230 --> 00:08:25.200
for data that proved that
you shouldn't trust them.

00:08:25.200 --> 00:08:28.840
And then trust ends up going
in the wrong direction.

00:08:28.840 --> 00:08:35.169
So I think it's important to
trust in little increments,

00:08:35.169 --> 00:08:37.926
and then measure it, see how
it's going, and then give more.

00:08:37.926 --> 00:08:41.330
Now when the betrayal is
larger, when it's really

00:08:41.330 --> 00:08:45.840
a betrayal of sort
of a character

00:08:45.840 --> 00:08:48.610
where people have really
violated something deep--

00:08:48.610 --> 00:08:50.760
my guess is every one of
you have trusted something

00:08:50.760 --> 00:08:53.660
in your life, and every one
of you has felt betrayed,

00:08:53.660 --> 00:08:54.160
you know?

00:08:54.160 --> 00:08:55.590
And it's a tough
thing to overcome.

00:08:55.590 --> 00:08:57.673
So I would say that if
it's one of those betrayals

00:08:57.673 --> 00:08:59.557
of character, the
odds are you're

00:08:59.557 --> 00:09:01.390
going to wake up in the
middle of the night,

00:09:01.390 --> 00:09:02.460
thinking about it.

00:09:02.460 --> 00:09:03.910
It's going to be the
first thing on your mind

00:09:03.910 --> 00:09:05.659
when you get up in the
morning, and you're

00:09:05.659 --> 00:09:07.410
going to feel bitter about it.

00:09:07.410 --> 00:09:09.860
My advice is get over
it as fast as you can.

00:09:09.860 --> 00:09:13.027
That may be years, really,
before you get over it.

00:09:13.027 --> 00:09:15.110
But the way you'll know
that you've gotten over it

00:09:15.110 --> 00:09:16.985
is you're starting to
think about the future.

00:09:16.985 --> 00:09:18.443
You're not thinking
about the past.

00:09:18.443 --> 00:09:20.700
You're not looking in the
rear view mirror and saying,

00:09:20.700 --> 00:09:23.660
I can't believe this
person did that to me.

00:09:23.660 --> 00:09:27.580
So I think you want to get to
the future as fast as you can.

00:09:27.580 --> 00:09:30.172
SPEAKER 1: And so
it's interesting,

00:09:30.172 --> 00:09:31.880
as we're talking about
betrayal and trust

00:09:31.880 --> 00:09:34.970
and with elections and all
the political climate that's

00:09:34.970 --> 00:09:39.210
currently happening right now,
there's a lot of constant--

00:09:39.210 --> 00:09:41.580
you know, there's a lot
of disrespect, I think,

00:09:41.580 --> 00:09:44.200
around the political community
right now of the bashing

00:09:44.200 --> 00:09:45.970
and talking down
upon each other.

00:09:45.970 --> 00:09:49.020
What are your views on
the political climate?

00:09:49.020 --> 00:09:52.830
And what advice would you
have for the candidates?

00:09:52.830 --> 00:09:54.240
JOEL PETERSON: It's toxic.

00:09:54.240 --> 00:09:57.940
And what happens is when you
get into polemics and people

00:09:57.940 --> 00:10:01.740
get far out on the edge, it's
very tough to knit things back.

00:10:01.740 --> 00:10:03.700
You know when you
have strained trust?

00:10:03.700 --> 00:10:04.540
It's very tough.

00:10:04.540 --> 00:10:07.540
So if people are thinking about
actually leading an enterprise

00:10:07.540 --> 00:10:11.350
after there's been that kind
of a battle, it's really tough.

00:10:11.350 --> 00:10:14.630
And so I was just reading
"The New York Times"

00:10:14.630 --> 00:10:18.280
that 2/3 of the electorate
trust neither of the leading

00:10:18.280 --> 00:10:19.410
candidates.

00:10:19.410 --> 00:10:20.746
That's shocking.

00:10:20.746 --> 00:10:24.804
For 2/3 of Americans not to
trust either of the leading

00:10:24.804 --> 00:10:25.304
candidates?

00:10:25.304 --> 00:10:27.240
I mean, I find that
just appalling.

00:10:27.240 --> 00:10:29.510
Well, what that
means is you can see

00:10:29.510 --> 00:10:32.060
that it's going to be very
tough to bring people together

00:10:32.060 --> 00:10:32.560
after that.

00:10:32.560 --> 00:10:36.450
So I don't feel great about it.

00:10:36.450 --> 00:10:38.979
SPEAKER 1: And is there
advice that you have?

00:10:38.979 --> 00:10:41.020
Can they overcome that
reputation that they have?

00:10:41.020 --> 00:10:42.910
Say, if they do win
the seat, knowing

00:10:42.910 --> 00:10:45.474
that 2/3 don't trust them,
how do they overcome that?

00:10:45.474 --> 00:10:47.390
JOEL PETERSON: So trust
is one of these things

00:10:47.390 --> 00:10:50.310
that you build up a
molecule at a time.

00:10:50.310 --> 00:10:54.505
You build trust a conversation
at a time in your life.

00:10:54.505 --> 00:10:57.260
And you can destroy
it in a single act.

00:10:57.260 --> 00:11:04.270
So I actually think that this
process of bashing is damaging.

00:11:04.270 --> 00:11:07.650
I also think that the American
people are the clientele.

00:11:07.650 --> 00:11:10.840
And so we're the ones who are
selecting the people that we're

00:11:10.840 --> 00:11:11.970
going to hire.

00:11:11.970 --> 00:11:13.720
Fundamentally,
we're hiring people

00:11:13.720 --> 00:11:15.890
to be the president
of the United States.

00:11:15.890 --> 00:11:18.490
So it says a lot about us.

00:11:18.490 --> 00:11:21.040
And I would say that everybody
in here's a millennial,

00:11:21.040 --> 00:11:23.639
it looks like to
me, pretty much.

00:11:23.639 --> 00:11:25.847
It's one of the great things
about-- well, maybe not.

00:11:25.847 --> 00:11:28.132
[LAUGHTER]

00:11:28.132 --> 00:11:29.410
Not David for sure.

00:11:29.410 --> 00:11:30.730
Not me for sure.

00:11:30.730 --> 00:11:32.552
But this is a company
of millennials.

00:11:32.552 --> 00:11:35.010
And you know, if you look at
the millennials, they really--

00:11:35.010 --> 00:11:37.180
so I get asked
this all the time.

00:11:37.180 --> 00:11:39.080
They're hardworking,
they're smart,

00:11:39.080 --> 00:11:41.700
they want to do the right
thing, they care about meaning,

00:11:41.700 --> 00:11:43.570
they care about
balance in their lives.

00:11:43.570 --> 00:11:45.500
But fundamentally,
I think they've

00:11:45.500 --> 00:11:48.350
become a bit of a
mistrustful generation.

00:11:48.350 --> 00:11:51.610
And if you look at the reasons,
I mean, they were told,

00:11:51.610 --> 00:11:53.042
buy a house.

00:11:53.042 --> 00:11:54.250
That's the right thing to do.

00:11:54.250 --> 00:11:56.541
And then they've seen their
neighbors be foreclosed on.

00:11:56.541 --> 00:11:57.780
They've said, get married.

00:11:57.780 --> 00:12:01.080
And they see their families--
divorce in their own families

00:12:01.080 --> 00:12:01.900
or neighbors.

00:12:01.900 --> 00:12:03.550
They were told, go to college.

00:12:03.550 --> 00:12:05.120
You know, get a college degree.

00:12:05.120 --> 00:12:07.090
And they find that people
get college degrees

00:12:07.090 --> 00:12:10.530
and they end up with a mountain
of debt they can't repay.

00:12:10.530 --> 00:12:11.430
And so on and on.

00:12:11.430 --> 00:12:13.880
A lot of these things
they've been told to trust,

00:12:13.880 --> 00:12:16.386
trust this stuff.

00:12:16.386 --> 00:12:18.010
Go to work for a
company, and then they

00:12:18.010 --> 00:12:19.720
find that people get laid off.

00:12:19.720 --> 00:12:22.121
So they've learned to be a
bit mistrustful, a bit wary.

00:12:22.121 --> 00:12:23.620
And there are good
reasons for that.

00:12:23.620 --> 00:12:27.510
So in some ways, we have an
electorate that's mistrustful,

00:12:27.510 --> 00:12:28.500
that's a bit angry.

00:12:28.500 --> 00:12:31.020
And so the candidates
speak to that.

00:12:31.020 --> 00:12:34.190
Candidates really are just
reflections of what's going on.

00:12:34.190 --> 00:12:36.530
And so I think when you have
that in the candidates--

00:12:36.530 --> 00:12:38.820
so I don't blame the
candidates altogether.

00:12:38.820 --> 00:12:41.131
I kind of say, this is
where we are right now.

00:12:41.131 --> 00:12:42.630
And I think it
really takes somebody

00:12:42.630 --> 00:12:45.440
to put their arms around us
and say, hey, what do we share?

00:12:45.440 --> 00:12:48.640
There's a lot more that
we share than divides us.

00:12:48.640 --> 00:12:50.820
SPEAKER 1: So as you're
describing millennials--

00:12:50.820 --> 00:12:53.111
and I think I'm probably one
of the older millennials--

00:12:53.111 --> 00:12:55.480
but that really
resonated with me.

00:12:55.480 --> 00:12:57.620
I think a lot of how I
think and approach things

00:12:57.620 --> 00:12:59.744
is very similar to what
you said with the weariness

00:12:59.744 --> 00:13:01.430
and the mistrust of
a lot of decisions

00:13:01.430 --> 00:13:03.440
we need to make in life.

00:13:03.440 --> 00:13:06.190
In your book, you talk about
different communication styles

00:13:06.190 --> 00:13:10.930
of how you can learn to
trust or kind of clearly

00:13:10.930 --> 00:13:13.517
communicate trust to others.

00:13:13.517 --> 00:13:15.850
Can you talk a little bit
about the communication styles

00:13:15.850 --> 00:13:17.290
and the methods?

00:13:17.290 --> 00:13:21.380
JOEL PETERSON: The most powerful
way to develop trust is to act.

00:13:21.380 --> 00:13:25.299
Whatever you do, if your words
and your actions sync up,

00:13:25.299 --> 00:13:26.340
people tend to trust you.

00:13:26.340 --> 00:13:28.160
People are super smart.

00:13:28.160 --> 00:13:32.360
So I've found that even
the newest receptionist

00:13:32.360 --> 00:13:35.500
in the company knew all kinds
of stuff and picked up on stuff,

00:13:35.500 --> 00:13:37.470
whether people were
trustworthy or not.

00:13:37.470 --> 00:13:39.011
So the first thing
is that you've got

00:13:39.011 --> 00:13:40.900
to sync up words and actions.

00:13:40.900 --> 00:13:44.280
If they're out of sync, it's
very hard to develop trust.

00:13:44.280 --> 00:13:47.270
The second communication thing
that I always tell to people

00:13:47.270 --> 00:13:50.450
is, part of communication
is listening.

00:13:50.450 --> 00:13:52.780
If I explain the most important
part of communication,

00:13:52.780 --> 00:13:55.034
if you've been around
a good listener,

00:13:55.034 --> 00:13:56.950
they tend to capture
what it is you're saying.

00:13:56.950 --> 00:14:00.540
And they tend to
listen until you've

00:14:00.540 --> 00:14:03.166
been able to
explicate or tell what

00:14:03.166 --> 00:14:04.290
it is you're talking about.

00:14:04.290 --> 00:14:07.200
They've captured it in a way
that they can reflect it.

00:14:07.200 --> 00:14:11.710
And if somebody can communicate
in that way as a good listener,

00:14:11.710 --> 00:14:13.134
they've done a whole lot.

00:14:13.134 --> 00:14:14.800
And then I think the
other thing I'd say

00:14:14.800 --> 00:14:17.270
is that in a
corporation, in a family,

00:14:17.270 --> 00:14:20.380
in any kind of an organization,
is communicate lavishly.

00:14:20.380 --> 00:14:22.712
What that means is you
don't withhold the bad news.

00:14:22.712 --> 00:14:24.170
You know, I see a
lot of people who

00:14:24.170 --> 00:14:27.360
try to manage-- [INAUDIBLE]
talking in the news business,

00:14:27.360 --> 00:14:30.640
you guys know that people
hold the bad news till Friday

00:14:30.640 --> 00:14:32.570
afternoon, and then dump it.

00:14:32.570 --> 00:14:34.869
All those kind of manipulations
people think work--

00:14:34.869 --> 00:14:36.410
AUDIENCE: But we in
the news business

00:14:36.410 --> 00:14:38.080
try to publish it
Friday morning.

00:14:38.080 --> 00:14:39.020
[LAUGHTER]

00:14:39.020 --> 00:14:40.900
JOEL PETERSON: Even
if it's not true?

00:14:40.900 --> 00:14:41.840
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:14:41.840 --> 00:14:42.673
JOEL PETERSON: Yeah.

00:14:42.673 --> 00:14:43.720
[LAUGH]

00:14:44.880 --> 00:14:49.010
But I think this
idea of disclosure,

00:14:49.010 --> 00:14:52.590
of telling people bad
news as well as good news.

00:14:52.590 --> 00:14:53.720
Because people are smart.

00:14:53.720 --> 00:14:54.560
People know.

00:14:54.560 --> 00:14:57.010
If you learn all of the
important news at the water

00:14:57.010 --> 00:15:00.140
cooler or in the
newspaper, you've

00:15:00.140 --> 00:15:02.876
actually damaged the trust
within the organization.

00:15:02.876 --> 00:15:04.709
So I think you have to
communicate bad news.

00:15:04.709 --> 00:15:09.564
You have to communicate before,
during, and after events.

00:15:09.564 --> 00:15:11.980
And a lot of times, people
think that if they just do one,

00:15:11.980 --> 00:15:15.060
or they can have a news
flash, and that's it.

00:15:15.060 --> 00:15:19.130
My experience is most
events have a long lead-up.

00:15:19.130 --> 00:15:22.210
They have kind of a crescendo
that something happens.

00:15:22.210 --> 00:15:23.840
And then there's
a period of time

00:15:23.840 --> 00:15:25.690
when there's kind
of a denouement.

00:15:25.690 --> 00:15:27.690
And I think really
effective communicators

00:15:27.690 --> 00:15:31.510
realize that people need to know
information all along the way.

00:15:31.510 --> 00:15:35.960
So I think those are three ways
to think about communication.

00:15:35.960 --> 00:15:37.750
SPEAKER 1: Thanks
for sharing that.

00:15:37.750 --> 00:15:39.965
And so given that
you need to be more

00:15:39.965 --> 00:15:41.340
transparent in
your communication

00:15:41.340 --> 00:15:45.500
