in the business environment

00:15:49.100 --> 00:15:51.520
as a leader yourself?

00:15:51.520 --> 00:15:55.560
And then I guess, what advice
do you have for us as Googlers

00:15:55.560 --> 00:15:57.985
to instill that type
of leadership quality

00:15:57.985 --> 00:16:00.087
in our future as we
continue to grow?

00:16:00.087 --> 00:16:02.420
JOEL PETERSON: So I've tried
to think about it two ways.

00:16:02.420 --> 00:16:04.331
One is sort of
broadly leading a team

00:16:04.331 --> 00:16:07.940
or whatever where you have
to communicate objectives.

00:16:07.940 --> 00:16:10.670
When I was a managing partner
at Trammell Crow Company,

00:16:10.670 --> 00:16:13.750
for example, I used to write
a partner's letter every two

00:16:13.750 --> 00:16:16.832
weeks, and I would make sure
that everybody heard from me,

00:16:16.832 --> 00:16:17.700
and [INAUDIBLE].

00:16:17.700 --> 00:16:22.250
And JetBlue, every Monday
we send out a letter,

00:16:22.250 --> 00:16:24.600
and it's from a member
of the management team,

00:16:24.600 --> 00:16:26.899
to all 19,000 employees.

00:16:26.899 --> 00:16:28.440
So there's that kind
of communication

00:16:28.440 --> 00:16:31.089
that keeps everybody on
top of whatever's going on.

00:16:31.089 --> 00:16:33.380
The other kind, though, is
I think a much more personal

00:16:33.380 --> 00:16:36.320
kind, which I think you can do
even if your enterprise doesn't

00:16:36.320 --> 00:16:36.990
do it.

00:16:36.990 --> 00:16:40.210
And to me, it's this notion
of a standing meeting.

00:16:40.210 --> 00:16:44.290
So wherever I am, I tend
to go around and stop

00:16:44.290 --> 00:16:47.900
in people's offices and just
say, how are things going?

00:16:47.900 --> 00:16:49.500
What are you working on now?

00:16:49.500 --> 00:16:50.750
What obstacles are you having?

00:16:50.750 --> 00:16:52.208
Is there anything
I can do to help?

00:16:52.208 --> 00:16:55.670
And then typically, it's nice
to ask them about their lives,

00:16:55.670 --> 00:16:58.730
about their family, and to
remember something about what

00:16:58.730 --> 00:17:00.230
was going on in their lives.

00:17:00.230 --> 00:17:02.840
I mean, caring about
people is actually

00:17:02.840 --> 00:17:04.460
a really powerful thing.

00:17:04.460 --> 00:17:08.470
And a lot of people don't do it,
or they think it's a technique.

00:17:08.470 --> 00:17:10.540
You actually have to care.

00:17:10.540 --> 00:17:11.849
It really has to matter to you.

00:17:11.849 --> 00:17:13.530
If you do that,
that communicates

00:17:13.530 --> 00:17:14.859
all kinds of things.

00:17:14.859 --> 00:17:18.329
If you don't, then people
see through it again.

00:17:18.329 --> 00:17:21.329
SPEAKER 1: And is that the
tool or the secret tool

00:17:21.329 --> 00:17:25.510
that you use to empower your
employees within the companies

00:17:25.510 --> 00:17:26.094
that you lead?

00:17:26.094 --> 00:17:27.593
JOEL PETERSON: I
don't think there's

00:17:27.593 --> 00:17:28.740
anything secret about it.

00:17:28.740 --> 00:17:32.910
I think-- I mean, it is
out of these conversations

00:17:32.910 --> 00:17:36.400
that you end up figuring out
who to empower and how much.

00:17:36.400 --> 00:17:39.660
My view of empowering people is,
ultimately what you want to do

00:17:39.660 --> 00:17:42.740
is empower people who are
closest to the customer.

00:17:42.740 --> 00:17:45.210
So it's wherever the action
is, you want people to feel

00:17:45.210 --> 00:17:47.260
empowered to make decisions.

00:17:47.260 --> 00:17:50.020
You get better decisions
if you can do that.

00:17:50.020 --> 00:17:51.925
But you can't do
it all of a sudden.

00:17:51.925 --> 00:17:54.300
You can't just dump all the
decisions of the organization

00:17:54.300 --> 00:17:57.240
on your youngest,
most remote people.

00:17:57.240 --> 00:17:59.790
So you have to do
it incrementally.

00:17:59.790 --> 00:18:01.254
And then you measure.

00:18:01.254 --> 00:18:02.670
So one of the
chapters in the book

00:18:02.670 --> 00:18:04.772
is about the power
of accountability,

00:18:04.772 --> 00:18:06.230
why there has to
be accountability.

00:18:06.230 --> 00:18:10.600
If you're going to trust people,
they have to be accountable.

00:18:10.600 --> 00:18:13.340
And so they need to know
what you're measuring.

00:18:13.340 --> 00:18:14.632
Otherwise, it's not real trust.

00:18:14.632 --> 00:18:16.173
You can surprise
them by, saying, oh,

00:18:16.173 --> 00:18:17.610
that's not what
we were measuring.

00:18:17.610 --> 00:18:21.804
So I think you kind of move
to something like that.

00:18:21.804 --> 00:18:23.970
SPEAKER 1: So I was just
