00:18:36.840 --> 00:18:39.490
How would you kind of
combine them together,

00:18:39.490 --> 00:18:42.960
or how do you see them all
in relation to one another

00:18:42.960 --> 00:18:45.260
in how you can live your
life in a powerful way

00:18:45.260 --> 00:18:46.577
and in an honest way?

00:18:46.577 --> 00:18:48.160
JOEL PETERSON: Well,
so I think you've

00:18:48.160 --> 00:18:50.850
mentioned about your virtues
that we all aspire to,

00:18:50.850 --> 00:18:53.660
and we all like in
our friends or spouses

00:18:53.660 --> 00:18:55.205
or significant others.

00:18:55.205 --> 00:18:56.540
Those seem [INAUDIBLE].

00:18:56.540 --> 00:18:58.990
I would say, though, that
I categorize all of those

00:18:58.990 --> 00:19:01.980
under the rubric of character.

00:19:01.980 --> 00:19:04.530
But that's only one
element of trust.

00:19:04.530 --> 00:19:06.560
If somebody has
high character, that

00:19:06.560 --> 00:19:08.570
is not enough to trust them.

00:19:08.570 --> 00:19:11.180
We think that this warm,
fuzzy feeling-- ooh, gosh.

00:19:11.180 --> 00:19:12.720
I really like her.

00:19:12.720 --> 00:19:14.090
Therefore, I trust her.

00:19:14.090 --> 00:19:16.750
But I was ask my
executives that come in

00:19:16.750 --> 00:19:19.100
to take these exec
courses at Stanford.

00:19:19.100 --> 00:19:23.490
Well, would you trust your mom,
whom you trust, high character,

00:19:23.490 --> 00:19:26.722
to fly a 747 to London?

00:19:26.722 --> 00:19:28.636
And they say, well, heck no.

00:19:28.636 --> 00:19:29.971
Well, why wouldn't you?

00:19:29.971 --> 00:19:31.970
Well, because she doesn't
know what she's doing.

00:19:31.970 --> 00:19:33.735
She's not competent.

00:19:33.735 --> 00:19:35.785
She's not competent to do that.

00:19:35.785 --> 00:19:37.160
So if you want to
trust somebody,

00:19:37.160 --> 00:19:40.206
it doesn't just
start with honestly.

00:19:40.206 --> 00:19:43.000
That's the feel-good
care element.

00:19:43.000 --> 00:19:44.984
There's an element
of competence.

00:19:44.984 --> 00:19:46.400
If you're going
to trust somebody,

00:19:46.400 --> 00:19:48.110
they have to be competent.

00:19:48.110 --> 00:19:50.550
And if you expect
to be trusted, you

00:19:50.550 --> 00:19:53.665
have to be competent, which
means you deliver on what

00:19:53.665 --> 00:19:54.790
you say you're going to do.

00:19:54.790 --> 00:19:57.330
And then the final
thing I tell people

00:19:57.330 --> 00:20:01.070
is, people that you trust have
to have the authority to act.

00:20:01.070 --> 00:20:03.412
There's no point in
telling David here

00:20:03.412 --> 00:20:04.870
who's a lawyer that
I'd really like

00:20:04.870 --> 00:20:07.530
not to pay taxes this year.

00:20:07.530 --> 00:20:08.980
And you're a lawyer.

00:20:08.980 --> 00:20:10.550
David has high character.

00:20:10.550 --> 00:20:11.910
He's very competent.

00:20:11.910 --> 00:20:13.640
So I'd just like
not to pay taxes.

00:20:13.640 --> 00:20:15.490
He doesn't have the
authority to do that.

00:20:15.490 --> 00:20:16.780
He can't make that happen.

00:20:16.780 --> 00:20:20.950
So for me to trust him to keep
me from paying taxes is folly.

00:20:20.950 --> 00:20:22.200
It's not smart trust.

00:20:22.200 --> 00:20:25.680
So trust is, I think, a
really hard-edged principle.

00:20:25.680 --> 00:20:28.350
And you can get
really good at being

00:20:28.350 --> 00:20:31.780
thoughtful about who you trust
by being kind of analytical,

00:20:31.780 --> 00:20:32.940
by factor analyzing.

00:20:32.940 --> 00:20:35.890
What is it that you're
really trusting?

00:20:35.890 --> 00:20:37.970
And so it is those things
that you mentioned,

00:20:37.970 --> 00:20:38.810
but it's not enough.

00:20:38.810 --> 00:20:40.990
It's inadequate.

00:20:40.990 --> 00:20:43.420
SPEAKER 1: Well, thanks
